BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/76ce7852-642f-476c-9b5b-7782224310e0.webp
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260609T114159Z
DESCRIPTION:As part of Shared Futures\, a public programme accompanying Beneath the Turning Sky\, we invite audiences into conversations with artists from the exhibition\, offering deeper insight into their creative processes\, research\, and ways of engaging with the world.\n\nFor the inaugural edition of the series\, artist Rupali Patil joins Gayatri Kodikal in conversation to explore ecofeminist perspectives on land\, labour\, and the body. Their dialogue will examine how systems of extraction and environmental degradation are experienced\, resisted\, and reimagined through artistic practice\, while reflecting on the forms of resilience\, care\, and collective resistance that emerge in times of ecological crisis.\n\nBeneath the Turning Sky brings together artists working across painting\, sculpture\, photography\, and textile practices\, illuminating contemporary debates around ecology\, technology\, development\, and our relationship with the environment. Through distinct visual languages\, the exhibition asks: How might art reshape our collective stewardship of the planet?\n\nExtending these questions beyond the gallery\, Shared Futures creates a space for exchange through lectures\, conversations\, workshops\, and other experimental formats. Across these encounters\, the series considers what the arts can offer in turbulent times and how creative practices can help forge new ways of thinking\, being\, and building solidarity.\n\nThis event is held in conjunction with our ongoing permanent exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. \n\n&nbsp\;
DTEND:20260620T123000Z
DTSTART:20260620T113000Z
SUMMARY:Shared Futures: Artist Conversations
UID:1306@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/shared-futures-artist-conversations/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Nocturnes-still-1-scaled.jpg
CATEGORIES:Film Screenings,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260604T072802Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Metamorphosis Film Junction\nAn immersive viewing experience of sound and imagery\, the film weaves together an intricate and poetic tapestry of our world. In the dense forests of Arunachal Pradesh\, ecologist Mansi sets out on a quest to study moths in one of the most vibrant places on earth. She teams up with Bicki\, a young man from the indigenous Bugun community\, to seek clues about what the future holds for the moths as temperatures rise. \n\nBy focusing on a small\, ephemeral\, nocturnal creature like the moth\, Nocturnes seeks to question a human-centric view of the world. The lush forest\, throbbing with a vast diversity of life\, emerges as a breath-taking character as the film responds to the symphony of sounds and the inherent rhythms of the trees\, the wind and the rain. The result is a rare and transformative experience that invites us all to look with more attention and care at the hidden interconnections in nature. \n\nThis event is held in conjunction with our ongoing permanent exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. 
DTEND:20260619T140000Z
DTSTART:20260619T123000Z
SUMMARY:Nocturnes
UID:1300@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/nocturnes/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/image-6.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260617T111125Z
DESCRIPTION:Before we say goodbye to the plants\, join us for one last curator-led walkthrough of the exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany\, and Empire. \n\nBetween the 17th and 20th centuries\, the Indian subcontinent was the site of extensive botanical surveys under colonial rule. Plant collection and classification were closely tied to imperial economic\, medical\, and political interests\, and botanical illustration played a central role in this project. Bringing together a new and historically significant collection of botanical art from this period\, the exhibition draws on recent scholarship to recover the often uncredited identities and histories of the Indian artists who made them.\n\nShrey Maurya\, curator of the exhibition and Research Director at Impart\, leads this walkthrough through the layered histories embedded in these artworks\, and their relevance to how we understand the natural world today.\n\n‘Paper Gardens’ marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260704T113000Z
DTSTART:20260704T103000Z
SUMMARY:Closing Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire
UID:1312@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/closing-paper-gardens-art-botany-and-empire/
END:VEVENT
