BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/HP-Slider-Images-Mobile-1.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260616T115600Z
DESCRIPTION:What does vulnerability look like? What does care feel like?\nThese are the questions that artist afra eisma leaves us with in warrior garments.\n\nJoin us for the final session of reflective feminist reading sessions\, developed in collaboration with Zubaan and facilitated by Laxmi Murthy. Together\, we will explore gender-based violence—its lived realities\, and the possibilities of resistance\, solidarity\, and healing. Through stories\, essays\, and personal reflections\, you are invited to engage with the exhibition at your own pace\, in a space that encourages listening\, sharing\, and care.\n\nNote: This is the final session in a series presented alongside Warrior Garments. Reading materials for each will be shared after registration.\n\nTrigger Warning: The sessions may include discussions on sexual violence.
DTEND:20260621T073000Z
DTSTART:20260621T053000Z
SUMMARY:Holding Space: Feminist Reading Circle
UID:1302@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/holding-space-feminist-reading-circle-3/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/image-5.png
CATEGORIES:Online Talk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260617T061057Z
DESCRIPTION:Lover's Tryst\; Rajasthan\, India\; 1750–1800\; Gum tempera and gold on paper\; 30.7 x 23 cm. Courtesy The Cleveland Museum of Art: Mr and Mrs William H Marlatt Fund\nAn Impart X MAP Symposium\nGarden of the Senses\n— A Sensory History of Indian Art\nLive on Zoom | 24-26 June 2026 | 7 pm (IST)\n\nWhat might taste\, touch\, scent\, sound\, and emotion reveal about the history of art?\n\nBringing together artists\, critics\, historians\, and practitioners\, this three-part series explores how sensory approaches can expand our understanding of South Asia’s art and cultural histories — through subjects ranging from court paintings and garden cultures to kitchens\, workshops\, and cities.\n\nPresented in collaboration with IMPART\, this series is held in conjunction with the exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire\, on view at MAP until 5 July 2026.\n\nScroll down to view the schedule\, learn more about the speakers\, and register for the sessions.\n\n[DIALOGUE 1]\n\nWays of Feelings — An Introduction to Sensory History\n24 June | Wednesday | 7 PM (IST)\n\nDr Fatima Quraishi\, Dr Preeti Bahadur Ramaswami\, Vinit Vyas\n\nDrawing on court miniatures from the Himalayas to the Deccan\, this session provides a general introduction to sensory approaches in art history. It considers what these works reveal about people\, places\, cultures\, and lived experiences across time\; what it means to feel an image rather than merely see it\; and how such an approach might open up new ways of imagining the past.\n\n[DIALOGUE 2]\n\nSensoria Indica — On Scents\, Sounds and Gardens\n25 June | Thursday | 7 PM (IST)\n\nBharti Lalwani\, Indu Antony\, Dr Murad Khan Mumtaz\, Dr Nicolas Roth\n\nMoving through fragrance and botany\, music and materiality\, scents and the city\, this discussion looks closely at how non-visual senses were woven into early modern Hindustani paintings and how they continue to influence contemporary art techniques.\n\n[DIALOGUE 3]\n\nMaking Sense — On Tastes\, Touch and Labour\n26 June | Friday | 7:00 PM IST\n\nDr Arun Kumar\, Mallory Cerkleski\, Dr Neha Vermani\n\nExamining early-modern Mughal kitchens\, colonial artisanal workshops in north India\, and toddy shops in contemporary Kerala\, this conversation foregrounds the labour behind these practices. Drawing on a wide range of archival\, visual\, and oral sources\, it studies the politics of touch\, taste\, and taste-making in the South Asian context.
DTEND:20260626T150000Z
DTSTART:20260624T133000Z
SUMMARY:Garden of the Senses  — A Sensory History of Indian Art
UID:1311@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/garden-of-the-senses-a-sensory-history-of-indian-art/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/DSC00282-scaled.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260617T060624Z
DESCRIPTION:Inspired by the tactile artwork The Known Universe\, featured in Beneath the Turning Sky\, this hands-on workshop invites participants to collaboratively imagine and create their own universe through a queer-affirmative lens. Drawing from the artwork’s exploration of belonging\, materiality\, labour\, and our relationship with the world around us\, participants will use personal objects\, storytelling\, and collective making to build worlds that centre care\, joy\, identity\, and community.\n\nParticipants are required to bring a small object that represents their sense of self\, home\, or belonging. The object should be no bigger than the palm of your hand. Facilitated by Mira Brunner\, the artists behind the piece\, this workshop offers a playful and creative space to reimagine the worlds we inhabit and the futures we wish to create.
DTEND:20260620T073000Z
DTSTART:20260620T053000Z
SUMMARY:Create Your Own Universe: A Queer World-Building Workshop
UID:1307@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/create-your-own-universe-a-queer-world-building-workshop/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/NOCTURNES-new-still-4-scaled.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260616T115225Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Metamorphosis Film Junction\nThe workshop evolves from the core ideas of the film Nocturnes. We will together experience\, discuss\, and go deeper into the interface between duration and attention through a range of guided individual and group exercises: listening to field recordings\, viewing film excerpts\, taking photographs and videos\, and recording sounds. You will have an opportunity to explore and interpret the world around you through images\, sounds\, and unexpected ways in which they interact and speak to each other. No prior technical knowledge is required. All we ask is for you to be present with an open and curious mind.\n\nAttending the screening of Nocturnes on 19 June is highly recommended. \n\nThis event is held in conjunction with our ongoing permanent exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. 
DTEND:20260620T083000Z
DTSTART:20260620T043000Z
SUMMARY:Between Seeing and Listening
UID:1301@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/between-seeing-and-listening/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Untitled-design.jpg
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260617T111249Z
DESCRIPTION:Developed alongside the exhibition of the same name\, the Paper Gardens catalogue brings together over a hundred botanical illustrations from the 17th to the 20th centuries\, tracing encounters between plants\, artists\, and institutions across continents and styles. Featuring essays by art historian Dr Holly Shaffer\, botanist Dr Henry J Noltie\, and writer Sumana Roy\, the book approaches botanical drawings as living documents.\nShrey Maurya\, Research Director of Impart and co-editor of the book\, will be in conversation with the book’s designer\, Tania Singh Khosla\, to discuss the possibilities and challenges of working with botanical illustrations in book form.\nReferencing her vast expertise with publication design — including past catalogues for MAP — Khosla will delve into the mechanics of working with such artworks\; discuss the narrative and aesthetic choices that informed her approach\; and reflect on how the book’s structure expands on the themes of the exhibition.\n\nThe exhibition\, ‘Paper Gardens’\, marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260704T073000Z
DTSTART:20260704T060000Z
SUMMARY:Botanicals And The Book: A Look Inside The Paper Gardens Catalogue
UID:1313@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/botanicals-and-the-book-a-look-inside-the-paper-gardens-catalogue-2/
END:VEVENT
